    "code": "N20.0",
    "rawCode": "N200",
    "shortDesc": "Calculus of kidney",
    "longDesc": "Calculus of kidney",
    "plainEnglish": "A kidney stone is a hard mineral deposit that forms inside your kidney when certain substances in your urine crystallize and clump together. These stones can cause severe pain in your back or side, especially when they move through the urinary tract, and may also cause blood in the urine or difficulty urinating. The stones form when you don't drink enough water, have certain dietary habits, or have conditions that make your urine too concentrated with minerals like calcium or uric acid.",
    "whoUses": "Urologists, nephrologists, and emergency medicine physicians commonly diagnose and treat kidney stones using this code, which frequently appears on EOB statements when patients receive imaging (CT scans, ultrasounds), procedures (lithotripsy, stent placement), or surgical interventions for stone management. Primary care physicians may also use this code during initial evaluation and referral.",
