    "code": "N39.0",
    "rawCode": "N390",
    "shortDesc": "Urinary tract infection, site not specified",
    "longDesc": "Urinary tract infection, site not specified",
    "plainEnglish": "A urinary tract infection (UTI) is a bacterial infection that occurs somewhere in the system that stores and eliminates urine from your body—this could be in the bladder, urethra, ureters, or kidneys—but the specific location hasn't been identified or documented. You might experience symptoms like painful or burning urination, urgency to urinate frequently, cloudy or bloody urine, or lower abdominal pain, though some people have no symptoms at all. This code is used when a doctor confirms you have a UTI but either hasn't yet determined or hasn't specified which part of the urinary system is infected.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, emergency medicine doctors, urologists, and nurse practitioners commonly use this code when diagnosing UTIs in urgent care or office settings. It frequently appears on patient EOB statements as it's one of the most common infections treated in outpatient and emergency settings.",
